== Stage 4: Theory-Constrained Postulate Generation

Based on cross-case analysis, Stage 4 involves the generation of working postulates that attempt to account for the observed phenomenological regularities. These postulates must satisfy two constraints: they must be consistent with the experiential data as structured by Stages 1–3, and they must not simply reinstate the separability assumption that the elusivity problem calls into question.

The postulates generated at this stage are explicitly provisional and subject to revision in light of new cases and new theoretical developments. We treat them as what James called "working hypotheses" rather than established findings.

== Stage 5: Community-of-Inquiry Validation

Stage 5 adapts the Peircean ideal of a self-correcting community of inquiry to the specific conditions of anomalous experience research. Proposed postulates are circulated to a standing group of researchers with diverse disciplinary backgrounds, including physics, neuroscience, philosophy, and anthropology, who are invited to identify inconsistencies, alternative interpretations, and empirical tests. Validation is achieved not by consensus but by the failure of sustained critical scrutiny to overturn the proposed postulate.

= Preliminary Findings

Application of the framework to forty-three experiencer testimonies, drawn from three distinct phenomenon-types (UAP close encounters, n = 18; near-death experiences, n = 14; high-dose psychedelic experiences, n = 11), yields several preliminary findings.

First, ontological shock, as characterised in Section 3, is consistently identifiable across all three phenomenon-types using the Stage 1 protocol. Interviewers with no prior acquaintance with each other's cases arrived at structurally convergent characterisations of the shock episode in forty-one of forty-three cases (95.3%).

Second, the three phenomenon-types exhibit both a shared structural core and characteristic differences. All three exhibit high scores on cognitive penetration and after-effect stability. UAP close encounters show the highest scores on somatic signature; near-death experiences show the most pronounced temporal restructuring; high-dose psychedelic experiences show the widest range of affective tone sub-categories.

Third, in eighteen of the forty-three cases, experiencer testimony was accompanied by independent corroboration — physiological data, witness testimony, or physical trace evidence — that was consistent with the experiential report and not explicable by reference to known physical processes alone. We do not regard this as decisive confirmation of any particular metaphysical hypothesis; we regard it as a finding that warrants continued investigation under a framework that does not presuppose its impossibility.

= Objections

We address three principal objections.

_Objection 1: Ontological shock is simply intense emotional arousal interpreted through culturally available narrative frameworks._ This objection has force as a general hypothesis but does not account for the cross-cultural structural consistency documented in Stage 3. Culturally variable narrative frameworks produce culturally variable experiential structures; the structural core we have identified across our sample is notably invariant across cultural contexts, educational backgrounds, and prior beliefs.

_Objection 2: Taking first-person reports as data conflates subjective appearance with objective fact._ This objection presupposes the separability assumption we have questioned. More importantly, it proves too much: all empirical data in consciousness science, including data from self-report measures and neuroimaging, depends at some stage on first-person report. Our proposal is not that first-person reports are infallible but that they are not automatically trumped by third-person observation in domains where the phenomena of interest are constitutively first-personal.

_Objection 3: The framework is unfalsifiable because any negative result can be attributed to elusivity._ This objection has force and we take it seriously. Our response is that the framework generates specific, testable predictions at each stage: predictions about cross-case structural consistency (Stage 3), about physiological correlates (Stage 2), and about the conditions under which corroborating physical evidence is most likely to be found (Stage 4). These predictions can be tested and disconfirmed. Elusivity is a datum to be explained, not an escape hatch.

= Conclusion

We have argued that the affective–cognitive disruption produced by genuine anomalous encounters constitutes a form of first-person evidence that a rigorous methodology for anomalous experience research must integrate rather than filter. The concept of ontological shock, developed in dialogue with James's radical empiricism and Husserlian phenomenology, provides a philosophically tractable framework for this integration. The five-stage methodology proposed here is a first attempt at operationalising this framework, and the preliminary findings reported in Section 5, while not conclusive, are sufficient to warrant continued development.

The broader implication of our argument is that anomalous experience research requires not merely better methods of the kind already in use but a different conception of what evidence is and what it is evidence of. We do not pretend to have resolved the deep philosophical questions at stake. We hope to have shown that those questions are tractable, that they admit of rigorous investigation, and that the investigation is worth pursuing.

